'''Cécile Manorohanta''' is a [[Madagascar|Malagasy]] politician, currently serving in the government of Madagascar as [[Interior minister|Deputy Prime Minister for the Interior]]. Previously she was [[Defense Minister|Minister of Defense]] from 2007 to 2009. 

Manorohanta was appointed as Defense Minister on 27 October 2007 in the government of Prime Minister [[Charles Rabemananjara]]. She was the first female defense minister in her country.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=598233 "Madagascan leader names new government"] [[The Sunday Times (South Africa)|The Times]], 27 October 2007</ref>

On 9 February 2009, Manorohanta announced her resignation, saying that "after all that has happened, I decide as of now to no longer remain part of this government,"<ref>[http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gA7e1eB8l_WeByiWnHnU5dBfjwTw Madagascar defense minister resigns]</ref> referring to the shooting on 7 February, during the [[2009 Malagasy protests]], in which police shot dead at least 50 protesters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2009/02/200927132745370579.html|title=Madagascar protesters shot dead|date=2009-02-08|accessdate=2009-02-08|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> Chief of military staff [[Mamy Ranaivoniarivo]] was appointed to replace Manorohanta on the same day.<ref>[http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hFbE7DLDNPZ5quC3WZX2dDJXIWKw "Defence minister quits over Madagascar bloodbath"], AFP, 9 February 2009.</ref>

Under Transitional President [[Andry Rajoelina]], Manorohanta was reappointed to the government as Deputy Prime Minister for the Interior on 8 September 2009.<ref>[http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5i4zhPstqdP0-N4V6wrdwoILtMSaA "SADC 'rejects, condemns' new Madagascar govt"], AFP, 8 September 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.madagascar-tribune.com/Un-gouvernement-de-31-membres,12686.html "Monja Roindefo; Un gouvernement de 31 membres"], ''Madagascar Tribune'', 9 September 2009 {{fr icon}}.</ref>

On 18 December 2009, Rajoelina dismissed Prime Minister [[Eugene Mangalaza]], whose appointment had been endorsed by opposition factions as part of a power-sharing agreement, and stated he would appoint Manorohanta in his place. However, on 20 December 2009 Rajoelina instead appointed [[Albert Camille Vital]] as Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8424084.stm | work=BBC News | title=Madagascar leader abandons deal | date=21 December 2009 | accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref>

