'''Milka Planinc''' ({{IPA-sh|mîːlka plǎnint͡s|pron}}; 21 November 1924 – 7 October 2010) was a [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] politician from [[Croatia]]. She served as a [[List of leaders of communist Yugoslavia|Prime Minister]] of [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]] from 1982 to 1986, the first and only woman to hold this office. Planinc was also in tern the first female [[head of government]] in a widely recognised [[communist country]],<ref name="Guardian-obituary"/> with the first in a [[List of historical unrecognized states|partially recognized]] communist country being [[Khertek Anchimaa-Toka]] of [[Tuvan People's Republic]], also the first female non hereditary head of state.<ref name = "Times Online Obituary">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article5269130.ece "Khertek Anchimaa-Toka: The World's First Female Head of State"]. [[Times Online]]. 2 October 2008. Retrieved 22 October 2009.</ref>

==Early life==
Planinc was born Milka Malada in a mixed [[Croats|ethnic Croat]] and [[Serbs of Croatia|ethnic Serb]] family<ref name="Guardian-obituary"/> in Žitnić, a small village near [[Drniš]], [[Dalmatia]]. She attended school, but with the onset of World War II her schooling was interrupted.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=112}} She joined the Communist Youth League in 1941,{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=112}} which was a pivotal year in Planinc’s life and for her country. [[Nazi Germany]] invaded Yugoslavia and divided the country among German, Italian, Hungarian, and Bulgarian occupying authorities.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=113}} Soon a resistance group known as the [[Partisan (military)|Partisans]] was formed, led by a locksmith named [[Josip Broz]] who called himself "Tito".{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=113}} Planinc waited impatiently for the day when she would be old enough to join the anti-Fascist Council for the National Liberation of Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=113}}

Aged 19, Planinc joined the [[Partisan (military)|Partisans]] and became extremely devoted to Tito.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=113}} In 1944 she joined the [[Communist party]].{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=114}} She became county commissar of the 11th Dalmatian Shock Brigade whose job it was to teach party principles and policies, and ensure party loyalty.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=113}} Planinc spent years working for the Partisans and the [[Communist]] party, and when they gained control of the entire region she enrolled in the Higher School of Administration in Zagreb to continue her education.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=116}} Partisan commander [[Simo Dubajić]] later alleged that Planinc was involved with the post-war [[Kočevski Rog massacre|massacre at Kočevski Rog]].<ref>[http://www.b92.net/info/vesti/index.php?yyyy=2005&mm=05&dd=31&nav_category=167 "Kardelj's dispatches found"], [[B92]] {{sr icon}}</ref>

In 1950, she married an engineer named Zvonko Planinc.<ref name="Guardian-obituary"/> The couple had a son and a daughter.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=116}}

==Political career==
Planinc began to pursue a full-time career within the [[League of Communists of Croatia]].{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=117}} She specialized in education, agitation, and propaganda, and in 1959 she was elected into the Croatian Central Committee, the executive body.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=117}}

Having served in a variety of posts in Zagreb, as the Secretary of the People’s Assembly of [[Trešnjevka]] in 1957 and then the Secretary of Cultural Affairs of the City of [[Zagreb]] in 1961, she became the Secretary of the City of Zagreb League of Communists Committee, and the Secretary for Education of the Socialist Republic of Croatia in 1963, a position in which she remained until 1965.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=117}}

Greater party acknowledgment did not come until 1966 when she was elected into the Presidium of the League of Communists of Croatia (LCC), and then to the executive committee of the LCC in 1968.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=117}} She served as the President of the Assembly of the Socialist Republic of Croatia 1967&ndash;1971.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}

After the events of [[Croatian Spring]], the leadership of LCC was removed, and Planinc became president of the Central Committee in 1971.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=117}} She made the decision to arrest [[Franjo Tuđman]], [[Marko Veselica]], [[Dražen Budiša]], [[Šime Đodan]] and [[Vlado Gotovac]], among others, who had all participated in the Croatian Spring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/64358/milka-planinc-o-savki-razisle-smo-se-ali-se-nikada-nismo-niti-svadale-niti-mrzile|title=Milka Planinc o Savki: 'Razišle smo se, ali se nikada nismo niti svađale niti mrzile'|trans_title=Milka Planinc on Savka: 'We went our separate ways, but we never argued or hated each other'|language=Croatian|publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]|author=Boris Bilas|date=8 August 2009|accessdate=23 July 2012|archivedate=23 July 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69NXfh4Lg}}</ref>  
She remained the Leader of the League of Communists of Croatia until 1982.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}

When Tito died in 1980, he left a plan for a rotation of eight leaders, with the leader coming from each federal unit in turn.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=117}}  On 29 April 1982, the Federal Conference of the Socialist Alliance of the Working People of Yugoslavia approved a list of ministers submitted by Planinc, and on 15 May 1982 a joint session of the National Assembly’s two houses named her head of the Federal Executive Council; thus she became prime minister.<ref name="OSA">Stankovic, Slobodan. [http://www.osa.ceu.hu/files/holdings/300/8/3/text/86-1-324.shtml Open Society Archives]. 6 May 1982 (retrieved on 15 April 2008)
</ref> She became the first woman to occupy such a high post in the country's 64-year history.<ref name="OSA"/> Planinc had a new governmental body, The Federal Executive Committee, and it consisted of 29 members.<ref name="OSA"/> All of the members of this committee were new, except for five that were members of the old committee.<ref name="OSA"/>

She would serve as the President of the Federal Executive Council (Prime Minister) of [[SFR Yugoslavia]] between 1982 and 1986. Her mandate as prime minister was remembered as the times when the government finally decided to regulate external debt of SFR Yugoslavia and to start to pay it back. In order to achieve necessary means, her cabinet implemented restrictive economic measures for a few years.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}

The [[1974 Yugoslav Constitution|1974 constitution]] had left the central government with very little authority, as the power was divided into the separate republics.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=118}} Planinc tried to re-focus the central government and gain international alliances with visits to [[United Kingdom|Britain]], the [[United States]], and [[Moscow]].  Though her visits to [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] gave her promises of economic support, her visit to [[Moscow]] was said to be with ''"nothing lost, and nothing gained"''.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=119}}

Planinc offered her resignation in October 1985, but this was not accepted.<ref>Meier, Viktor; ''Yugoslavia: a history of its demise'', Routledge, 1999. (p. 15)</ref> On February 12, 1986 Planinc's government submitted a request to the [[International Monetary Fund]] for advanced surveillance.<ref>Boughton, James M.; ''Silent revolution: the International Monetary Fund, 1979-1989'', International Monetary Fund, 2001. (p. 433)</ref> The request was approved a month later. Her term ended in May 1986, and before long she became a member of the LCY Central Committee.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=120}}

==After politics==

The former prime minister spent the rest of her time living through bitter days of war with the disestablishment of Communism, the fall of the [[Berlin wall]], and the fighting between Croats and Serbs.{{sfn|Opfell|1993|p=120}} In 1993 her husband died, and in 1994 her son Zoran committed suicide.<ref name="Guardian-obituary">
{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/oct/10/milka-planinc-obituary
|accessdate=2011-02-12
|title=Milka Planinc obituary | work=The Guardian
|date=2010-10-10
 |location=London
 |first=Dejan
 |last=Djokic
}}</ref>

From the late 1990s until her death, Milka Planinc was using a wheelchair and rarely left her apartment.<ref>[http://www.jutarnji.hr/magazin/clanak/art-2007,9,1,milka_planinc,88312.jl "Milka Planinc: Partisan and Homeland wars are anti-fascist"], ''[[Jutarnji list]]''</ref> She resided in [[Zagreb]] until her death on 7 October 2010, aged 85.<ref>[http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/preminula-milka-planinc-bivsa-premijerka-sfrj/516660.aspx "Preminula Milka Planinc"], [[Index.hr]] {{hr icon}}</ref> She was buried at the [[Mirogoj]] <ref>Gradska groblja Zagreb: Milka Planinc, Mirogoj RKT-51-II/I-202</ref>  

